<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1437,617,1603]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,617,643]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
A pair of processes on male abdominal sternite VI short (&lt;
<quantity box="[909,1012,617,644]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="mm" value="0.05">0.05 mm</quantity>
), widely separated, strongly divergent, apically somewhat pointed (
<figureCitation box="[469,560,653,679]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1780,1804]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1757]" captionTargetId="figure-18@13.[151,1435,181,1757]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. Male abdominal sternite VIs of Colocasiomyia colocasiae (Duda) (B in anteroventral view, C in lateral view), C. stamenicola (Carson &amp; Okada) (D in anterior view) and all species of the C. cristata subgroup (A in ventral view, E‒R in anterior view): A, C. ecornuta sp. nov.; E, C. grandis sp. nov.; F, C. vieti sp. nov.; G, C. cristata de Meijere; H, C. matthewsi sp. nov.; I, C. sulawesiana Okada &amp; Yafuso; J, C. kinabaluana sp. nov.; K, C. kotana sp. nov.; L, C. sabahana sp. nov.; M, C. sarawakana sp. nov.; N, C. pistilicola (Carson &amp; Okada); O, C. xenalocasiae (Okada); P, C. diconica (Toda &amp; Okada); Q, C. sumatrana sp. nov.; and R, C. leucocasiae sp. nov. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766420/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 9K</figureCitation>
). Phallal sheath apically vertically dilated in lateral view, subapically without any appendages (
<figureCitation box="[345,473,689,715]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="34.[151,250,1841,1865]" captionTargetBox="[274,1313,181,1818]" captionTargetId="figure-22@34.[274,1313,181,1818]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURE 22. Colocasiomyia kotana Toda &amp; Takano, sp. nov. (♂ and ♀ paratypes and puparium from Kota Kinabalu, Sabah, Malaysia). A, Male abdominal sternites (ventral view); B, female abdominal sternites (ventral view); C, periphallic organs (lateral view); D, phallic organs (lateral view); E, ditto (ventral view); F, female terminalia (lateral view); G, anterior spiracles of puparium (dorsal view); H, puparium (ventral habitus; inset: caudal-most portion); I, mouth hook; J, cephalopharyngeal skeleton. Scale bars: 0.1 mm in A–F and J, 1.0 mm in H." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766450" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766450/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 22D,E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1437,617,1603]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,724,750]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Description</emphasis>
(
<specimenCount box="[352,373,724,750]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount box="[425,447,725,751]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
; not repeating characters common to 
<taxonomicName authority="Takano &amp; Gao &amp; Hu &amp; Li &amp; Yafuso &amp; Suwito &amp; Repin &amp; Pungga &amp; Meleng &amp; Kaliang &amp; Chong &amp; Toda, 2021" authorityName="Takano &amp; Gao &amp; Hu &amp; Li &amp; Yafuso &amp; Suwito &amp; Repin &amp; Pungga &amp; Meleng &amp; Kaliang &amp; Chong &amp; Toda" authorityYear="2021" box="[862,1033,724,751]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Colocasiomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kinabaluana" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[862,881,725,751]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[893,1033,724,750]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">kinabaluana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1039,1127,724,750]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1039,1127,724,750]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
). Head. Supracervical setae 6–7 per side, nearly straight, as long as inner occipital setae. Cibarial, posterior sensillum 0–1 per side. Supralateral setae outside prementum approximately 4 per side.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1437,617,1603]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
Male terminalia. Epandrium posteroventrally roundish on margin but not extended, with approximately 2 setae on lateral portion and 22–24 setae on ventral portion of each side (
<figureCitation box="[882,985,866,892]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="34.[151,250,1841,1865]" captionTargetBox="[274,1313,181,1818]" captionTargetId="figure-22@34.[274,1313,181,1818]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURE 22. Colocasiomyia kotana Toda &amp; Takano, sp. nov. (♂ and ♀ paratypes and puparium from Kota Kinabalu, Sabah, Malaysia). A, Male abdominal sternites (ventral view); B, female abdominal sternites (ventral view); C, periphallic organs (lateral view); D, phallic organs (lateral view); E, ditto (ventral view); F, female terminalia (lateral view); G, anterior spiracles of puparium (dorsal view); H, puparium (ventral habitus; inset: caudal-most portion); I, mouth hook; J, cephalopharyngeal skeleton. Scale bars: 0.1 mm in A–F and J, 1.0 mm in H." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766450" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766450/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 22C</figureCitation>
). Cercus nearly oval, slightly constricted ventrosubapically, pubescent on dorsal 2/5, with 54–55 setae (
<figureCitation box="[847,950,901,928]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="34.[151,250,1841,1865]" captionTargetBox="[274,1313,181,1818]" captionTargetId="figure-22@34.[274,1313,181,1818]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURE 22. Colocasiomyia kotana Toda &amp; Takano, sp. nov. (♂ and ♀ paratypes and puparium from Kota Kinabalu, Sabah, Malaysia). A, Male abdominal sternites (ventral view); B, female abdominal sternites (ventral view); C, periphallic organs (lateral view); D, phallic organs (lateral view); E, ditto (ventral view); F, female terminalia (lateral view); G, anterior spiracles of puparium (dorsal view); H, puparium (ventral habitus; inset: caudal-most portion); I, mouth hook; J, cephalopharyngeal skeleton. Scale bars: 0.1 mm in A–F and J, 1.0 mm in H." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766450" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766450/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 22C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1437,617,1603]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
Female terminalia. Oviscapt shorter than phallus (apodeme + sheath), with 16–19 ovisensilla; distal portion spatulate, roundish apically (
<figureCitation box="[474,574,972,999]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="34.[151,250,1841,1865]" captionTargetBox="[274,1313,181,1818]" captionTargetId="figure-22@34.[274,1313,181,1818]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURE 22. Colocasiomyia kotana Toda &amp; Takano, sp. nov. (♂ and ♀ paratypes and puparium from Kota Kinabalu, Sabah, Malaysia). A, Male abdominal sternites (ventral view); B, female abdominal sternites (ventral view); C, periphallic organs (lateral view); D, phallic organs (lateral view); E, ditto (ventral view); F, female terminalia (lateral view); G, anterior spiracles of puparium (dorsal view); H, puparium (ventral habitus; inset: caudal-most portion); I, mouth hook; J, cephalopharyngeal skeleton. Scale bars: 0.1 mm in A–F and J, 1.0 mm in H." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766450" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766450/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 22F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1437,617,1603]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
Indices (range of 
<specimenCount box="[393,442,1008,1034]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="male">10♂</specimenCount>
and 
<specimenCount box="[495,546,1008,1034]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="female">10♀</specimenCount>
): FW/HW = 0.55–0.65, ch/o = 0.36–0.53, prorb = 0.87–1.03, rcorb = 0.28–0.44, vb = 0.23–0.39, dcl = 0.57–0.93, sctl = 0.82–0.97, sterno = 0.67–0.99, orbito = 0.40–0.63, dcp = 1.13–1.34, sctlp = 1.27–1.64, C = 1.50–2.06, 4c = 1.07–1.29, 4v = 1.47–1.96, 5x = 0.83–1.12, ac = 2.69–3.40, M = 0.32–0.47.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1437,617,1603]" box="[199,1386,1114,1141]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
Puparium (3rd instar larva). Anterior spiracle with a bundle of approximately 5 short branches (
<figureCitation box="[1269,1374,1114,1140]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="34.[151,250,1841,1865]" captionTargetBox="[274,1313,181,1818]" captionTargetId="figure-22@34.[274,1313,181,1818]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURE 22. Colocasiomyia kotana Toda &amp; Takano, sp. nov. (♂ and ♀ paratypes and puparium from Kota Kinabalu, Sabah, Malaysia). A, Male abdominal sternites (ventral view); B, female abdominal sternites (ventral view); C, periphallic organs (lateral view); D, phallic organs (lateral view); E, ditto (ventral view); F, female terminalia (lateral view); G, anterior spiracles of puparium (dorsal view); H, puparium (ventral habitus; inset: caudal-most portion); I, mouth hook; J, cephalopharyngeal skeleton. Scale bars: 0.1 mm in A–F and J, 1.0 mm in H." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766450" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766450/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 22G</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
