<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="33.[151,1437,617,1603]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1469,1495]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[592,765,1469,1496]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Colocasiomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sulawesiana">
<emphasis box="[592,611,1469,1495]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[627,765,1469,1495]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">sulawesiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the apical, vertical dilation of phallal sheath (
<figureCitation box="[1322,1432,1469,1495]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1855,1879]" captionTargetBox="[203,1385,181,1830]" captionTargetId="figure-22@30.[203,1385,181,1831]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 20. Colocasiomyia sulawesiana Okada &amp; Yafuso (♂, ♀ and puparium from Enrekang, South Sulawesi, Indonesia). A, Male abdominal sternites (ventral view); B, female abdominal sternites (ventral view); C, periphallic organs (lateral view); D, phallic organs (lateral view); E, ditto (ventral view); F, female terminalia (lateral view); G, anterior spiracles of puparium (dorsal view); H, puparium (ventral habitus; inset: caudal-most portion); I, mouth hook; J, cephalopharyngeal skeleton. Scale bars: 0.1 mm in A–F and J, 1.0 mm in H." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766446" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766446/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Figs 20D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[151,204,1505,1531]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="34.[151,250,1841,1865]" captionTargetBox="[274,1313,181,1818]" captionTargetId="figure-22@34.[274,1313,181,1818]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURE 22. Colocasiomyia kotana Toda &amp; Takano, sp. nov. (♂ and ♀ paratypes and puparium from Kota Kinabalu, Sabah, Malaysia). A, Male abdominal sternites (ventral view); B, female abdominal sternites (ventral view); C, periphallic organs (lateral view); D, phallic organs (lateral view); E, ditto (ventral view); F, female terminalia (lateral view); G, anterior spiracles of puparium (dorsal view); H, puparium (ventral habitus; inset: caudal-most portion); I, mouth hook; J, cephalopharyngeal skeleton. Scale bars: 0.1 mm in A–F and J, 1.0 mm in H." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766450" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766450/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">22D</figureCitation>
), but can be distinguished from it by other diagnostic characters and the oviscapt shorter than the phallus (apodeme + sheath).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
